<HEAD>Opposition Leader Says Guatemala Lagging On Peace Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An opposition leader who was arrested when she returned from exile said Friday that <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> is lagging behind other Central American nations in seeking peace with rebels. <PERSON> Rigoberta </PERSON> <PERSON> Menchu </PERSON> and another activist were arrested Monday, then released after being held for seven hours. She returned to exile in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Friday. Despite her arrest, Ms. <PERSON> Menchu </PERSON> said she moved freely during her stay here, despite periodic death threats that she called `` normal and of not much importance.'' She said she and three other members of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guatemalan </ORGANIZATION> had discussed with Roman Catholic Archbishop <PERSON> Prespero </PERSON> <PERSON> Penados </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrio </PERSON> whether exiles can safely return to <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. `` We had great success,'' she said at the airport before departing for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, but gave no details. Travel plans of the the other exiles, <PERSON> Rolando </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Montalvo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Rue </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marta </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, were not known. Ms. <PERSON> Menchu </PERSON> and <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> Montalvo </PERSON> were arrested and charged with crimes `` against the internal security of the nation,'' but a judge subsequently dismissed the charges for lack of evidence. Speaking with reporters at the airport, Ms. <PERSON> Menchu </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> is far from meeting provisions of a Central American peace plan signed Aug. 7 by the presidents of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOC