<HEAD>Radio Says Bofors Bribed Indian Family for Weapons Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Swedish radio said Friday it had obtained documents supporting allegations that a family of Indian financiers received $ 13.7 million in connection with a Swedish arms sale to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. It said the documents included telex messages between the Swedish firm <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> and two <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> banks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in 1986 dealing with accounts under the control of London-based members of the <PERSON> Hinduja </PERSON> family. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> also reported the allegations. <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinduja </PERSON>, one of four brothers active in the family operations, called the information `` a complete fabrication'' in a statement to the Hindu. <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Per </PERSON> <PERSON> Mossberg </PERSON> was quoted as denying the allegations. The telex messages indicated the account holder was promised a 10 percent commission on a $ 1.4 billion Indian contract for 155mm howitzers made by <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s largest arms manufacturer, the Swedish radio said. It described the <PERSON> Hindujas </PERSON> as being close to Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The broadcast said money from <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> passed through accounts held by the <PERSON> Hinduja </PERSON> family at the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. It claimed the deposits were transferred to <ORGANIZATION> Sangam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, a company <ORGANIZATION> Swedish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said was owned by the <PERSON> Hinduja </PERSON> family. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s government was facing allegations of corruption when it negotiated the deal with <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 and made the condition that no middlemen be used. A Swedish investigation last June found that <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> paid up to $ 40 million to individuals, but the company legally blocked access to further information. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> committee dealing with the case adopted its final report Friday, but the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said investigators had `` drawn a blank.'' The report was not made public. It is to be presented to Parliament next Friday. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> pledged anew that the government would punish any Indian who profited from the deal illegally, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. He was in <LOCATION> Madras </LOCATION> for a two-day <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> meeting.
