y. The former criminal division chief then proceeded to lay out `` an oral indictment'' of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> to the president, said the source, focusing on <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s relationship with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> is under indictment in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> scandal. The administration source said <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> told the president that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had violated the standards of ethical conduct for executive branch employees spelled out in a 1965 executive order. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, according to the source, said that in other similar instances of possible impropriety, <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers would be placed on administrative leave, disciplined or dismissed. `` The president was very attentive,'' said the source, adding that `` it was clear he was hearing for the first time that not everything is well in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>.'' The ethical standards say employees should avoid any action which could create the appearance of using public office for private gain, giving preferential treatment to any organization or person or making a government decision outside official channels. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and White House counsel A.B. <PERSON> Culvahouse </PERSON> also attended the meeting. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was summoned to a 40-minute meeting with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> immediately afterward. According to <PERSON> Korten </PERSON>, the president told <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> at the end of their meeting that he was `` satisfied and supportive'' of the attorney general. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> left his post officially on Friday, 3 -LCB- weeks after resigning to protest <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s continued tenure as attorney general. Independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, who has been conducting a criminal investigation of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> since last May 11, is expected to issue a report of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s activites if he does n't seek an indictment of the attorney general. It is likely the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsibility </ORGANIZATION> will then examine ethical questions raised as a result of <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s probe and will recommend to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> whether <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> should be disciplined or fired.
