<HEAD>Test Shows No Recurrence Of Breast Cancer For First Lady</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mammogram of <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s right breast shows no sign of cancer, the White House says. While the first lady went to <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> to have her six-month checkup following removal of her cancerous left breast, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had dental X-rays done there. The first couple flew by helicopter Friday to the suburban <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> military facility from the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, remained there for less than a half-hour, then went to Camp David for the weekend. `` The president and first lady completed their routine radiological procedures,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> physician Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> said. `` The president had a series of routine dental X-rays in the dental clinic, while Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had her first post-operative mammogram,'' he said. `` The mammogram was negative. No immediate treatment of any kind is required as a result of today's procedures on the president and first lady.'' The White House had said earlier that the examinations were not prompted by any current physicial problems of either of the Reagans. The Reagans did not answer reporters' questions when they left the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or on arrival or departure from the hospital. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, however, made an `` A-OK'' thumb-and-forefinger sign, indicating things went well. The last time the 77-year-old president visited the hospital was in January, when he underwent his semi-annual checkup for colon cancer. He has had regular checkups every January and June since he underwent surgery for an intestinal malignancy in July 1985. <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s press secretary, said, `` It's wise and routine to check the other breast'' after surgery of the kind the first lady had six months ago. She said the first lady has had periodic examinations since her operation Oct. 17, 1987, but this was her first X-ray of the right breast. Mrs. <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> said the couple wanted to have the results of Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s exam promptly `` so they could send her off for a comfortable, worry-free weekend.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, 66, had her breast removed after doctors discovered a quarter-inch cancerous lesion. She chose to undergo a modified radical mastectomy, which involves the removal of the entire breast and some lymph nodes. Mrs. <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> said that not only was it time for the first lady's six-month checkup, but the president could use the time `` to get his dental X-rays taken, rather than usually doing it at the White House. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> usually has a cleaning and checkup every three months at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but that the president planned to have a `` panoramic'' X-ray done this time in order to get a full-view picture of his mouth. The White House has X-ray machines that take pictures of parts of the mouth, but does not have the larger machine that pans the entire mouth area, he said. Panoramic radiographs, or X-rays that provide an overall view of the teeth and jaws, are used to diagnose problems ranging from cavities to tumors.
