<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 2,500 photographs from the <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> assassination file were destroyed because they were unneeded duplicates that took up filing space, a police spokesman says. Commander <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON>, responding to questions about the destruction disclosed earlier this week, said Friday the explanation came from a retired police officer who was very involved in the case. He declined to give the officer's name, saying, `` He has been retired for some time and is disinclined to get involved.'' But he said the man `` has an independent recollection'' of events relating to the pictures. In the aftermath of <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s assassination at the Ambassador Hotel on June 5, 1968, he said, police took photographs of every possible angle of the crime scene. `` What happened is there were many hundreds of photographs taken, thousands of photographs,'' <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> said. `` And many copies of each photograph were copied for us and for each agency involved.'' `` What were destroyed were superfluous duplicates that amounted to a lot of redundancy,'' he said. `` There was no need to keep them. Filing space was a consideration.'' The police department's voluminous file on the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> assassination was released for the first time Tuesday, and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Archivist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> noted a certificate showing that 2,410 photographs were burned by police two months after <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s death Police earlier had conceded they destroyed ceiling panels and part of a door jamb from the kitchen of the Ambassador that became central to investigation of whether a second gun might have been fired at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> senator. <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>, a Jordanian immigrant, was convicted of murdering <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON