<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The concrete and steel rubble from <LOCATION> L'Ambiance </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> has long been cleared away, but the impact of the decade's most devastating construction accident still is being felt in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Lawmakers have been pushing for changes in construction-safety laws since the partially built <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, apartment complex collapsed one year ago today, leaving 28 workers dead. Proposals have ranged from tinkering with the accident reporting requirements and stiffening criminal penalties in fatal construction accidents to creating a separate construction agency outside the often-criticized <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` Obviously the price is too high in all the lives lost to ever think of it as having a silver lining,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn. `` But given that all of that ca n't be changed, I do think it can be used ... to remind people in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and remind people in <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'' of problems in the construction industry Rep. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Shays </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., who was a state representative when <PERSON> L'Ambiance </PERSON> collapsed, has devoted much of his time to the accident since coming to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to replace the late Rep. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> But the freshman congressman is frustrated at the slow-moving gears of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` Like most victims of crimes, you have the victims of L'Ambiance who are seeing a fairly unresponsive government, or at least a government that has responded slowly,'' <PERSON> Shays </PERSON> said in an interview this week. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said he is drafting legislation to increase criminal penalties for contractors convicted in fatal construction accidents. The current maximum penalty is six months in prison and a $ 10,000 fine for willful violation of <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> standards. At the request of lawmakers, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing whether to change its reporting standards. Under current regulations, only accidents with a death or at least five injuries have to be reported. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> critics point to an accident in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, shortly before the L'Ambiance collapse that involved the same contractor and the same type of problem that investigators say triggered the <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> accident. But the <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION> accident went unreported because only one worker was injured. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, who labeled the current reporting requirements `` absurd,'' believes knowledge of the <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION> accident could have prevented L'Ambiance. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikelson </PERSON> said the reporting requirement is still under review. The agency also is reviewing its regulations on the lift-slab construction method used by <PERSON> L'Ambiance </PERSON> builders that was implicated in the collapse. Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., is pushing a measure that would put the L'Ambiance fines in a special trust fund for the victims' families <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> fears the heavy fines will drive the contractors into bankruptcy, making them unable to pay damages that could be awarded in pending civil suits. Some lawmakers are embracing the idea of making a separate construction division within <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>, while the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> wants to create a separate construction agency. Congressional supporters said, however, that they do not expect action this year. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapping </PERSON>, director of safety and health for the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said he does not hold out hope for significant changes because of L'Ambiance. `` In'78 we had the <LOCATION> Willow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> -LRB- cooling tower -RRB- accident -LRB- in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> -RRB- and we had 51 people killed there and nothing came out of that,'' Lapping said. Such criticism of <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> was reignited by the <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> collapse, with charges that the agency has too few inspectors and relies too heavily on industry self-regulation. But <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials defend their policing policies. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, in its vision when it imagined what <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> would be like, wanted an inspector on every job site 24 hours a day, it would have said so,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Mikelson </PERSON>. `` It made employers accountable for safety and health, knowing full well the government would n't have inspectors at every site in the country.'' <PERSON> Mikelson </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> has made changes in recent years, including imposing heavier fines such as those at L'Ambiance and severely penalizing project contractors when they fail to properly oversee subcontractors. `` The bottom line is when employers show a strong commitment to safety and health, workers sustain far fewer injures,'' he said.
