<HEAD>Pilot Lands On Dark Road With Guidance From Car's Taillights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLEGAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> `` Butch'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> could n't make much of a living as a race driver by following other cars. But he may owe his life to the car whose taillights he followed before landing his disabled airplane. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> Coopersville </LOCATION>, safely landed his six-passenger Aerostar 600 about 10 p.m. Thursday on the northbound lane of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> 40 about two miles north of here. `` At night, it's very hard to pick out roads, if not impossible,'' he said. `` Basically I chased the taillights. Whoever he is he saved my life and does n't know it.'' The driver of the car had not been identified by late Friday, said Deputy <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Allegan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, the defending <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Speed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> stock car racing champion, said he was en route from <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Muskegon </LOCATION> when the plane's right engine blew a gasket and he had to make an emergency landing.
