<HEAD>Investigator Says Mob Organized Into `Cells' Like Terrorist Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An investigator who almost became the first <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent inducted into an organized crime family says he was pulled out of the mob by his <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> superiors after being ordered to kill a gangster from a rival group. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> felt _ and so did I _ that this was a good time for getting out, because everybody was being killed,'' <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pistone </PERSON> told senators, explaining that he was given the hit assignment during a mob civil war. <PERSON> Pistone </PERSON> also told members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Permanent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> on Investigations there's a `` surprising similarity'' between the structure of organized crime families and terrorist groups. He said `` a strict need-to-know policy is enforced,'' and fellow mobsters often avoid telling each other their last names. <PERSON> Pistone </PERSON>, who spent six years working undercover with the mob, said he was scheduled to become a `` made'' member of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> family in December 1981 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> abruptly ended his operation a half-year after two <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> factions began a civil war, he said. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> said that to this day, no agent has ever become a formal `` made'' member of the mob rather than an associate. <PERSON> Pistone </PERSON> testified from behind a screen because he has been relocated and changed his appearance. But he has told his story before, in court testimony and in a book on his six years posing as a small-time but successful jewel thief and burglar, <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brasco </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pistone </PERSON>'s testimony in trials resulted in more than 200 indictments and more than 100 convictions of organized crime members. Explaining the workings of mob families, <PERSON> Pistone </PERSON> said: `` There is a surprising similarity which marks the inner-workings of the Mafia and contemporary terrorist organizations. `` The families are broken down into small, separate cells, commonly called crews. `` In all likelihood, a member of one crew may not even know who are the members of another crew in his own family.'' He said `` gambling is probably the most important source of income'' for traditional organized crime families. Gambling supports other mob activities, such as drug buys, payoffs, lawyer's fees, and investments into legitimate businesses, he said
