<HEAD>Yost Says Coast Guard Patrol Cuts Could Be Leading To Drug Trade
Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> says severe cutbacks in air and sea drug patrols by the financially strapped agency could be leading to an increase in drug trafficking along <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coasts. `` The smugglers, when they ship, do n't send us an invoice,'' said Adm. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` But we do have intelligence that indicates the awareness by the smugglers that the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has cut back its patrols by ship and by air. `` I can only surmise that that influences their shipping schedules'' and that there is `` some intention of taking advantage of that,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, faced with a $ 100 million budget shortfall, earlier this year permanently shut down dozens of stations, resulting in $ 40 million in savings. To cover the remaining $ 60 million, <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> ordered a 55 percent across-the-board reduction of sea and air missions for drug interdiction and routine search-and-rescue patrols. The cutbacks have been in effect for about three months. `` Fifty-five percent of my ships are sitting alongside the dock and planes are on the runways,'' the commandant said in interviews this week with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think that's a travesty,'' he said. `` I really think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people, having paid money for the ships and aircraft, and ... paying the salary of the young men and women who they've trained to do these jobs, to have them sitting on the runway and tied up at the dock That ought to make the taxpayer angry.'' Last month, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to transfer $ 60 million in other <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATI