<FIRST>r a PM-GlobalClassroom Bjt   04-23 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Global Classroom, Bjt,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students In Four Countries Play Diplomat Via Computer Links</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEB RIECHMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 College students in 10 states and three countries are linking up by computer to simulate global bargaining for peace. But they're finding make-believe hostilities are often as touchy as in real life. In the first few days of the exercise this semester, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> rejected <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s offer to end their war as `` treachery'' and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> dispatched a flurry of communiques calling the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` offensive.'' The 700 students are playing diplomat as part of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Negotiation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Simulations </ORGANIZATION> program, based at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're not doing an adequate job in American education of teaching how to live and function in an interdependent world,'' said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkenfeld </PERSON>, a government and politics professor at the college who co-directs the program. `` It's only been in recent years that we have discovered a need to become more of a part of issues that other countries find important.'' One scenario envisioned by the students, who work six months in the future, proved all too real. `` We assassinated -LRB- <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> about three months before it really happened,'' said <PERSON> Wilkenfeld </PERSON>, who encourages students to seek solutions through peaceful negotiation. `` We felt badly about that.'' ICONS began in 1981 with a grant from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. In its early days, the program involved three or four universities. This semester, 15 universities are participating through computer links from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. The computer also links <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> students to others in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Messages during the five-week simulation often are sent in foreign languages and must be translated with care so sensitive correspondence is not misunderstood. With students living in various time zones, setting up computer conferences often becomes a logistical nightmare. The simulations are based on a scenario of world events written before the game begins each semester. The scenario takes what's happening in the world and projects it six to eight months ahead, <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> said That way, students are not tempted to read newspapers and magazines looking for negotiating tips and strategies, she said. In the first few days of this semester's simulation, the Soviets, played by students at <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Provo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, sent out more than 100 messages, said <PERSON> Doreen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, simulation director and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>'s research faculty. `` A lot of it was cold war rhetoric and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> -LRB- students at <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> -RRB- sent a response saying it was not pleased with what it called propaganda,'' <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> said. Two days later, the `` Soviets'' rebutted: `` The Soviet leadership and people were deeply wounded and pained by the offensive and insensitive communique received from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this week,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> team wrote. `` We are all concerned and troubled to find that the cold war still rages in the hearts of American leaders.'' Meanwhile, the Iranian team, played by a different group of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> students, was busy composing a reply to the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> team's offer to terminate its involvement in the Iran-Iraq war `` <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> sent out a message saying they were unilaterally withdrawing from the war, returning all Iranian POWs, returning all borders to original pre-war positions,'' said <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinchuck </PERSON>, a member of the Iranian team. `` We flatly rejected it and said it was ` filled with duplicity and treachery and horrific lies.'''
