<HEAD>Church Urges End To U.S. Sanctions, Saying Panama Has Suffered
Enough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is calling on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to lift economic sanctions imposed in an attempt to oust Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. It says <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has suffered enough. `` We can not continue like this,'' the church hierarchy lamented in an eight-page pastoral letter made public Friday. The letter says the economic crisis brought on by the sanctions has meant `` misery and desperation'' for thousands of Panamanians and sparked an exodus `` that is beginning to have worrisome dimensions.'' The letter, signed by Archbishop <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> and the nation's 10 bishops, also expressed concern about rising crime and worry that the nation is being turned into `` a sinister battle camp.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s de facto leader and head of its 15,000-strong <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, was indicted in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on federal drug trafficking charges in February. The sanctions, imposed since, froze Panamanian assets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and barred payments to the Noriega-controlled administration by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens and organizations. Combined with closures of the banks and a two-week strike in March, the measures have brought <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s economy to a virtual standstill. In its letter, the church says the sanctions have dealt a blow to all Panamanians, but especially to the poorest. It said the measures `` exceed any strategy of political pressure and constitute by themselves a threat to the life of our people. `` They are therefore morally unjust. Because of that, we demand that they be suspended immediately. In the same way, we reject all forms of military intervention.'' The church described as `` the gravest part of the situation'' the lack of dialogue between the government and <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s opponents It urged both sides to negotiate and end to the crisis and said it was willing to mediate the dispute. The church agreed at the end of March to mediate talks between the two sides, but suspended the effort a week later. Financial analysts, meanwhile, said the government was looking for an international organization to step in and help it process a backlog of checks accumulated during the bank shutdown. The government has been frustrated in its efforts to arrange a clearing-house operation with a private European or a Latin American bank. A financial analyst, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the government was turning to an international organization because it would be `` beyond the scope of -LRB- any in -RRB- the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' It was not clear which international organization would have the capability to act as a bank and process the thousands of accumulated checks. Banks closed the first week of March after customers began a run on some local institutions. The run was touched off when President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> was deposed Feb. 26 after he tried to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>.
