<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Archbishop of <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION> Lord <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, a kindly, craggy Christian and brilliant debater who traveled the world in his passion to unite its divided churches, died early today, the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> said. He was 83. <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> was president of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> from 1961 to 1968. The church press office said in a statement that he died at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION>, a residence for elderly people in <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, after being ill for several weeks with bronchial pneumonia. His wife, <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, was at his side when he died peacefully at about 2 a.m. -LRB- 9 p.m. EDT Friday -RRB-. As Archbishop of <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION> from 1961 to 1974, he was spiritual head of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and leader of the world's 70 million Anglicans, including the 3 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians. <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> took a liberal stand on a wide variety of political and social issues of his day. He condemned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> during the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War, called for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to discard its nuclear weapons unilaterally and campaigned for relaxation of the laws restricting homosexuality, divorce and abortion. <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> demanded the abolition of the death penalty, was an outspoken opponent of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid policy of racial separation and opposed restrictions on the admission of <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> immigrants into <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. At his enthronement as Archbishop of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> described his objectives as `` the unity of Christians.'' The Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> was at the time in process of a long decline, with dwindling church attendance and a diminishing role in the everyday lives of ordinary Britons. But <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> pushed the Church toward Christian reunion, which he predicted might come about before the end of this century, and made it aware of the world beyond <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. His passion to reunite the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> churches _ the Nonconformist, the Anglican, the Eastern Orthodox, and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, divided over the centuries _ took him to more countries than any other Archbishop of Canterbury before him. <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> was bitterly disappointed when the General Synod of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in 1972 rejected union with the Methodists. His air of craggy Christian kindness, as one newspaper described it, inspired trust and confidence among those who met him. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> was born on Nov. 14, 1904, the son of a lecturer in mathematics at <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. His paternal grandfather was a Congregationalist minister and his maternal grandfather was an Anglican clergyman. He was educated at <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, ordained in 1928, and became Bishop of <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION> in 1952 and <LOCATION> Archbishop </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1956. <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> was made a life peer on his retirement as archbishop in 1974 and took the title of Lord <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION>. He was succeeded by <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Coggan </PERSON>, who retired from the post in 1980. The current Archbishop of <LOCATION> Canterbury </LOCATION> is <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Runcie </PERSON>. A funeral service for <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> will be held in historic <ORGANIZATION> Canterbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> in southeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and a memorial service is also planned at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Westminster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abbey </ORGANIZATION>, the statement said. No dates have yet been set.
