<HEAD>College Administrators, Faculty Discuss Campus Racism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Increasing racial tensions on campus in recent years can be partly blamed on the `` self-centered'' ethics of students in the 1980s, educators and students were told at a conference. Not only have colleges failed to teach students about ethics, but the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has undermined gains in civil rights, contributing to a rise in racism, sexism and homophobia on campuses, some educators said. `` There's been a reversal in students from the 1960s,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a psychologist and professor emeritus at the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, who has researched the effects of segregation on children. `` They are more self-centered and less socially conscious.'' The conference at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was attended Friday by more than 250 teachers, administrators and students from about 30 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> colleges. Sponsored by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christians </ORGANIZATION> and Jews, its intent was to alert college leaders to the problems of intolerance and suggest possible solutions. But the educators said recent student protests over minority concerns at a number of colleges nationwide were encouraging. `` In part it's a good thing in the sense that it reflects a determination by minority kids not to take this treatment,'' said <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, professor of Education at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>, where students occupied an administration building in February to protest campus racism. Those who attended the conference were treated to their own bit of protest when a group of student demonstrators took the stage even though the state's <ORGANIZATION> Chancellor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollander </PERSON>, refused them permission to speak. <PERSON> Hollander </PERSON> said later he was `` delighted'' to see them insist on speaking out. `` I've waited 10 years for students to show that kind of interest,'' he said. <PERSON> Hollander </PERSON> said organizers asked colleges to send students and officials to the conference `` who hold the power'' to make campuses aware of the state's effort to curb intolerance. The protesters spoke up after the keynote speech by Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>. They criticized the pace of reform and said conference organizers failed to invite student and community activists. `` We feel this is just a PR event to appease the community and falsely give the sense that the colleges are resolving racist relationships,'' said <PERSON> Salaam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ismail </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION>, which represents colleges statewide. The protesters had kind words for <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON>, mayor since 1981, who urged administrators to preach against intolerance and ensure that graduates are able to contribute to a diverse society. He said changing demographics, rising immigration from <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, competition from <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries and a stagnant economy require that Americans work together in a spirit of cooperation. <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> said students should gain an `` education in reality'' by volunteering for community service and that universities should strive to develop minority leaders. Earlier Friday, in <LOCATION> Williamstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, about 30 minority students took over a dean's office at <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. A spokesman for the protesters said that black, Hispanic, Asian and Polynesian students occupied <ORGANIZATION> Jenness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to protest what they say is the administration's unwillingness to address minority concerns at the prestigious liberal arts college. Also Friday, a group of minority students and <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> officials reached agreement to end the students' four-day occupation of the college president's office. The agreement calls for the university to increase the number of minority faculty members and students.
