<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sinhalese rebels attacked the country's main air force base and battled troops for four hours before fleeing with stolen weapons. Officials said at least seven rebels and five servicemen were killed. Also Friday, guerrillas from the same group raided a radio station and stole communications equipment, authorities said. The military said the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> rebels ignited bombs `` as diversionary measures'' and stabbed two guards Friday night to enter <LOCATION> Katunayake </LOCATION> air base, 16 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The officials, who under briefing rules spoke on condition of anonymity, said five rebels, 24 servicemen and four policemen were injured in the air base battle, during which flights were halted at the adjacent <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> international airport. At least three rebels were captured, but their comrades managed to escape with at least 30 Chinese made T-56 rifles and a machine gun, the officials said. It was the rebel group's second attack on the air base. On June 8, a similar attack was repulsed. The rebels also attacked a radio station of the government-owned Posts and <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said Telecommunication officer J.M. <PERSON> Peries </PERSON>. <PERSON> Peries </PERSON> said two employees were stabbed and were in critical condition today. He said the rebels stole radio equipment, but some of it was later recovered. The People's <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> began as a radical Marxist group, but now champions rights of the island's majority Sinhalese. It was outlawed after a failed 1971 attempt to overthrow the government, and regrouped in 1986. The front has opposed the July 29 peace accord between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, which was aimed at ending the four-year separatist rebellion by the minority Tamils. The front contends the accord makes too many concessions to the Tamils and has vowed to kill anyone who supports it. The Tamils, who are mainly Hindu, compose about 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. They claim they are discriminated against by the <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION>, who make up 75 percent of the population and control the government.
