ecording; a request for comment was not returned. An <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> statement said the agency `` can no longer assure taxpayers of the deductibility of contributions to <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION>.'' However, it said past contributions are fully deductible. On Wednesday, the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, affirmed a lower court ruling that the bankruptcy court did not have the authority to issue a preliminary injunction preventing the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> from revoking the ministry's tax-exempt status. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said the ministry may appeal. If so, contributions by individuals would still be deductible up to $ 1,000 until the appeal is decided, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said. The government appealed the <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> reorganization plan approved Dec. 29 by the bankruptcy court in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and still opposes it. The plan, which anticipated <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> would remain tax exempt, divides the ministry into non-profit and for-profit corporations.
