<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> half-sang, half-spoke some of the <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stones </ORGANIZATION>' greatest hits from the witness stand as he tried to prove he did n't steal a song from a reggae musician. <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> swayed to the beat and came close to singing Friday as he recited for a judge, jury and fans who packed the courtroom, `` Jumpin' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Flash </PERSON>, it's a gas, gas, gas.'' <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> was trying to show how he uses repetition in his lyrics, as part of his defense against a charge by <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>, who is suing for copyright infringement, claiming <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s 1985 solo hit `` Just Another Night'' was copied from his 1979 song of the same name. The choruses in both songs use the phrase `` Just another night'' repeatedly. <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> has denied he stole the song, which he said he did n't hear until the suit was filed in 1986 He has testified for two days, playing tapes of the song as it was written and arranged in 1983 and 1984 to try to show the independent development of the piece. In Friday's session, he quoted lyrics from `` <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugar </PERSON>,'' `` Miss You,'' and `` Let's Spend the Night Together.'' <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> testified that repetition is common in popular music. Tapes were played of at least six different versions of the tune, recorded in various places with various people in 1984. The version that was released was recorded in May 1984 in <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, with a drummer named <PERSON> Sly </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunbar </PERSON>. Alley claims <PERSON> Dunbar </PERSON> played for his recording in 1979. <PERSON> Dunbar </PERSON> has testified that he did n't remember whether he played for Alley or not. <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> testified that the title and lyrics to the song went through a metamorphosis, starting with `` Another Night,'' and `` just another something else'' while he was `` messing around'' to develop the music. He could n't remember when he finished the lyrics or title. <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> admitting playing reggae music with the late reggae musician <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Tosh </PERSON>, but said he did n't tend to listen to radio stations that played that kind of music. He said he acknowledged works of other artists and paid them royalties. <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s lawyers have said <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s version netted as much as $ 6 million. The chorus of <LOCATION> Alley </LOCATION>'s song goes, `` Can I spend another, just another night, just another night, just another night with you.'' <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s lines are, `` Give me just another night, just another night with you. Give me just another kiss, just before the dawn breaks through.'' After his testimony, expected to continue Monday, <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> signed autographs and told reporters he thought the case was going well.
