t. <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> flew the distance from <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heraklion </LOCATION> military airfield in 3 hours, 54 minutes, faster than anticipated, and landed at 11 a.m. -LRB- 4 a.m. EDT -RRB-. Project organizers had estimated a flight time of at least five hours at a speed of around 14 miles an hour. Officials at <LOCATION> Heraklion </LOCATION> airport attributed the quicker flight to a 3 - to 4-knot tailwind <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 broke two records. First it shattered the mark for straight-line human-powered flight set in 1979, when <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> pedaled the Gossamer Albatross 22.5 miles across the English Channel. Then it broke the world record for human-powered flight, set by a <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 prototype, <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION>, which flew 37.2 miles around <LOCATION> Edwards </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in January 1987. <PERSON> Kanellopoulos </PERSON> smiled at reporters as he waited for the all-clear to take off in <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>. `` The flight belongs to <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. We together are going to realize and keep the myth. And of course this is the best way to visit <LOCATION> Santorini </LOCATION>,'' he said as he was being sealed into the ultra-light plane. Essential requirements for the flight were a calm sea, southerly winds of less than 3 knots, temperatures under 70 degrees and visibility to the horizon, according to <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bussolari </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> aeronautics professor in charge of flight operations. The flight also was intended to emulate the 3,500-year-old myth of <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION>, said to have flapped his way across the <LOCAT