<HEAD>Car Bomb In Tripoli Kills 50</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to raise reference to crowded market and
include background on Ramadan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A TNT-laden pickup truck exploded today in a crowded vegetable market in the northern port city of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, killing at least 50 people and wounding 80 others, police said. The 8:45 a.m. -LRB- 2:45 a.m. EDT -RRB- explosion knocked down several buildings, gutted shops and set fire to dozens of cars in the low-income <LOCATION> Tabbaneh </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s second largest city, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The explosion occurred as Moslem shoppers filled the market on the seventh day of the holy month of <LOCATION> Ramadan </LOCATION>, when observing Moslems fast during daylight hours. It was the worst car bombing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in nearly three years. Police said the pickup, apparently used to transport vegetables, had been loaded with about 220 pounds of TNT. No group has claimed responsibility for the bombing, and police said they had no clue as to who was to blame. Civil defense teams dug through the rubble looking for trapped people. `` It was a real massacre. Several pedestrians and vendors were torn to pieces,'' said a police spokesman, who could not be identified under standing regulations. He said Syrian troops in charge of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>'s security cordoned off the blast area as ambulances with wailing sirens took casualties to hospitals. Car bombs are a by-product of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 13-year-old civil war between Moslems and Christians. More than 100,000 people have been killed since fighting broke out in 1975. A car bomb exploded outside an ice cream parlor in <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION> on June 29, 1985, killing 50 people and wounding 110 as they celebrated the Fitr feast marking the end of <LOCATION> Ramadan </LOCATION>. Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem, condemned today's car bombing as a `` barbaric atrocity.'' `` All hands must team up to stop these executioners from committing further such crimes,'' he said. The city has a predominantly <LOCATION> Sunni </LOCATION> population of 850,000. There have been four bombings in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION> in the last three months in which five people have been killed and 15 wounded. But police said none of them involved a car rigged with explosives. At least 57 people were killed and 288 wounded in 16 car bombings in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> last year.
