<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposing Forces Flex Muscles to Prepare for Afghan Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 200 Soviet trucks and armored vehicles lumbered out of the capital at dawn Saturday for <LOCATION> Lowgar </LOCATION> province, where Moslem guerrillas have stepped up attacks as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> prepares its troops to withdraw. Many ground convoys and transport planes have been leaving <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in recent days to resupply Soviet positions and the vulnerable Afghan army, according to residents and Western diplomats. The Soviets agreed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to withdraw their estimated 115,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> more than eight years after <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> intervened to prop up the Marxist government. The withdrawal is to begin May 15. But the agreement is far from a peace accord. Guerrilla activities, including bombings in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> itself, have increased since February with the approach of spring and the melting of snow in the northern <LOCATION> Hindu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kush </LOCATION> and other mountain ranges. An alliance of seven Moslem guerrilla groups, whose headquarters are across the Afghan-Pakistani frontier, rejected the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord because it does not guarantee a cutoff of Soviet aid to President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s Afghan government. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, will not halt its arms supplies to the guerrillas until the Soviets stop supplying <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s troops. Meanwhile, the Soviets are are preparing for an escalation of guerrilla attacks in areas that will be the last to be vacated, according to foreign analysts. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s rugged geography has made it a nightmare for foreign armies since <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> the Great's short-lived conquest in the fourth century. Soviet watchposts on the road around <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> show signs of recent fortification. There is fresh concrete and stonework around Soviet sentry posts. Bunkers are newly draped with camouflage netting, Western diplomats said. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, hub of Soviet operations, is expected to be one of the last two cities the Soviets leave before the final withdrawal deadline of Feb. 15, 1989. The other is <LOCATION> Mazar-e-Sharif </LOCATION>, 40 miles south of the Soviet border on a dusty plain along the <LOCATION> Oxus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. During a tightly supervised seven-and-a-half hour visit arranged by the Afghan government on Friday, several signs of Soviet presence were visible there. Soviet army fuel trucks were parked near 20 Afghan air force MIG-21 fighter planes at the airport, a dozen Soviet soldiers went about their work, and storefronts showed the Cyrillic lettering used by the Soviets. According to Western diplomats and Afghan officials, all speaking on condition of anonymity, the Soviet pullout will probably start at their most exposed positions. These include bases near the Pakistani border. Meanwhile, the Soviets have plenty to worry about. According to a report compiled by Western diplomats, 22 bombs exploded in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in March, compared with 10 in February. They included magnetic bombs with timing devices that can be attached to vehicles, one diplomat said. Other guerrilla activities in recent weeks included curtailing movement on roads linking <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> with other major cities, according to the diplomat and residents. The diplomat said the guerrillas cut the road to <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION>, 75 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, on April 14. A reporter who flew over the road a week later saw only a dozen vehicles on a normally well-traveled section of the road. <LOCATION> Lowgar </LOCATION> province, which abuts the <LOCATION> Kabul-Ghazni </LOCATION> road, is `` very insecure,'' one Western source said. Indeed, the Soviet convoy that headed there Saturday showed signs of apprehension. It included eight T-62 tanks, at least a dozen armored personnel carriers, a score or more of trucks loaded with coal, and about 10 trucks carrying communications gear. Many trucks had metal plates that covered the lower half of the windshield on the driver's side and left only a brick-sized opening on the passenger's side. The drivers, many of whom appeared to be teen-agers, wore helmets and flak jackets. Some trucks were mounted with anti-aircraft guns. The guerrillas do not have aircraft, so the guns would presumably be used to attack their mountain positions.
</TEXT>
