<HEAD>Eight Islanders Rescued In Pacific After Drifting 29 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight <LOCATION> Kiribati </LOCATION> islanders adrift in a canoe for 29 days were rescued by an American tuna boat in the western <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, but the survivors said a woman and child died during the ordeal, according to a fishing industry official. Friday's rescue occurred some 1,100 miles from <LOCATION> Kiribati </LOCATION>, an island nation once known as the <LOCATION> Gilbert </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> August </PERSON> <PERSON> Felando </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tuna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Machado </PERSON>, master of the J.M. <PERSON> Martinac </PERSON>, reported the rescue of the three women and five men, <PERSON> Felando </PERSON> said. The survivors were taken abord the fishing boat and were headed for <LOCATION> Ponape </LOCATION>, part of the Federated States of <LOCATION> Micronesia </LOCATION>. They told <PERSON> Machado </PERSON> that a 2-year-old child and 27-year-old woman had died while they were adrift, said <PERSON> Felando </PERSON>. Those aboard the motorized canoe survived on rainwater and fresh fish after the engine failed during a trip from one island in the <LOCATION> Kiribati </LOCATION> chain to another, he said. The bodies of the dead woman and child were thrown overboard, he said.
