<FIRST>r w AM-WelfareReform     04-23 0960</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welfare Reform,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Welfare Overhaul Reflects Changed Society</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Overwhelming dissatisfaction with the welfare system is pushing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> toward major revisions in a program that started 53 years ago, before working women, teen-age mothers and child poverty were commonplace. The overhaul bills passed last year by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> acknowledge, as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill puts it, `` the vastly changed family arrangements of the intervening half century'' since the start of the Aid to Families with Dependent Children program. Both bills stress family responsibility and community obligation _ parental responsibility to support children and the community's obligation to make that feasible through expanded education and training opportunities And, to varying degrees, both bills would improve benefits for families who absolutely must rely on government assistance. Preliminary estimates by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> put the five-year cost of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill at $ 7.1 billion and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill at $ 2.8 billion. Whatever emerges from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will be more extensive than the $ 913 million plan backed by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, and is likely to draw a veto. Nevertheless, liberals and conservatives remain convinced that the system must be changed and many of them are in agreement on how to do it. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill is co-sponsored by a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. And while the House bill was passed without <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> backing, some Republicans indicated they could accept the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approach. Following is a comparison of major provisions in the two bills. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill may be amended on the floor, and the final product likely will combine features of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bills.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CASH BENEFITS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Senate: Changes AFDC to the Child Support Supplement Program. Requires all states to provide assistance to two-parent families in which the principal wage-earner is unemployed -LRB- currently an option picked up by half the states -RRB-, but benefits may be limited to six months. No change in the amount of earnings or child care costs that states must disregard in determining who gets benefits. House: Changes AFDC to the Family Support Program. Requires all states to provide assistance to two-parent families in which the principal wage-earner is unemployed. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> must recommend a national minimum benefit level within two years. States would receive a 25 percent increase in their federal matching share for any benefit increases between Oct. 1, 1988 and Oct. 1, 1991.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WORK</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>Basic Program</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Senate: States would replace the existing, small-scale Work Incentive program -LRB- WIN -RRB- with a comprehensive Job Opportunities and Basic Skills -LRB- JOBS -RRB- program. JOBS must include basic education and skills training plus other activities chosen by the states. House: States would replace WIN with a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, Training and Work -LRB- NETWork -RRB- program. The program must offer high school, remedial education, bilingual education and other specific activities. Community work experience, also known as workfare, must teach marketable skills and last no longer than six months.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Who Must Participate</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Senate: Able-bodied adults, including parents of children over age 3 or, at state option, age 1. If the child is under 6, required participation is limited to 24 hours a week. States must guarantee that child care is available. The federal government helps pay for child care and transportation. House: Able-bodied adults, including parents of children over age 3 or, at state option, age 1. If the child is under 6, required participation is limited to 20 hours a week. States with the lower age requirement must demonstrate that infant care is available for $ 200 a month or less. The federal government helps pay for child care and transportation costs.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Wages</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Senate: People do not have to accept a job if it pays less than their cash benefits combined with food stamps and Medicaid, unless the state makes up the difference with a supplemental benefit. House: Wages must be at least equal to whatever is highest _ the federal minimum wage, the state minimum wage or the pay rate for people in similar positions with the same employer. People do not have to accept jobs if the result is a net loss of income, including the insurance value of Medicaid.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Financing</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Senate: Federal government pays for 90 percent of the JOBS program up to the amount the states received last year under WIN. After that the federal contribution would range from 60 to 80 percent, except that administrative costs are split 50-50. Federal outlays are capped at $ 3 billion over five years; states are only expected to seek about one-third of that amount as they gear up their programs. House: Similar, except no cap on federal spending.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Work Transition</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Senate: States must provide child care for nine months to families that lose cash benefits due to earnings. Families must contribute to the cost. States must continue Medicaid for six months for such families, and may offer Medicaid for another six months to those with incomes below 185 percent of the federal poverty standard. Those above poverty level _ $ 11,650 for a family of four _ would be a charged a premium. House: States must provide child care for at least a year to families losing benefits due to earnings, unless family income in prior quarter was more than 150 percent of the poverty level. Families must contribute on a sliding fee scale. No Medicaid provision.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CHILD SUPPORT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>: Federal government would pay 90 percent of cost of lab tests used to establish paternity. Immediate wage-withholding required for all new or modified support orders enforced by state child support agency and for earlier orders if the agency requests. House: Immediate wage-withholding required for all orders issued or modified in the state and being enforced by the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
