<HEAD>Massachusetts Health Care Plan Could Be `Godsend'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON> believes his rising medical claims for a diabetic condition cost him his job, along with his company health insurance, but today he has hope in a new state law that he thinks will `` save myself and my family from potential financial ruin.'' <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' universal health care act was signed into law last week by Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a Democratic presidential contender who has touted it as an example for the rest of the country. The first-in-the-nation measure promises to make affordable health insurance available to all residents, rich or poor, working or unemployed, by 1992. <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON>, 53, knows something about health insurance. The job he lost was as a chief fraud investigator for a major <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> insurance company, his employer of 13 years. While other factors may have been involved in his termination, <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON> is convinced that the claims he filed for six $ 1,000 diabetes-related eye operations played a major role. And since he began working as a self-employed financial consultant, <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON> has found himself `` effectively in a Catch-22 situation'' in trying to get health insurance because his diabetes is considered a non-coverable, pre-existing condition. `` My efforts have indicated to me I could n't even get -LRB- a policy -RRB- that would cover diabetes, irrespective of the dollars of premium I were able to pay,'' he said. `` In other words, I can get coverage except for the coverage that I need.'' Enter the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> universal health care plan, under which by 1992, or possibly sooner, the state will broker pooled insurance for small businesses and individuals which participants can buy into on a sliding fee schedule based on their income. The details of what these plans will offer will be decided later by the new state agency that will manage the system. But <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' health policy adviser, said pre-existing conditions will definitely be covered. `` This is really landmark legislation,'' <PERSON> McFarland </PERSON> said. `` It's recognizing, in my judgment, that health care is a right, rather than a privilege. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says the four-year phase-in will cost the state $ 645.2 million, minus about $ 22.5 million in projected Medicaid cost-cutting. But some estimates have run as high as $ 1.2 billion. The law would extend coverage to about 600,000 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> residents under age 65 currently without health insurance, or roughly one of every 10 people in the commonwealth. This would be done in stages and through a variety of approaches, from extending Medicaid benefits for disabled adults and children to state - brokered, pooled insurance for small businesses and individuals By 1992, all employers with more than five full-time employees must offer health insurance coverage or pay an unemployment surcharge to help the state provide this coverage to the uninsured. <PERSON> Jeannette </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON>, 52, lives in <LOCATION> Athol </LOCATION> with her healthy 14-year-old daughter and her 68-year-old husband, who has chronic emphysema and has n't been able to work for a dozen years. When her family was younger and she had five children living at home, <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> briefly went on welfare. But she hated the condescension she felt from neighbors and welfare workers so she found work in part-time jobs that would allow her to continue caring for her homebound husband. Today, <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> does light cleaning for a company that recently began offering health insurance to full-time employees. But <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> is n't covered because she only works about 20 hours a week. <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> gets free indigent medical care for herself and her daughter through her local hospital's emergency room. Her husband's major medical expenses are covered by Medicare, but she still has to pay for the seven medications he has to take, costing $ 40 to $ 45 a week. `` What breaks me up is that I can apply for welfare, I can apply for Medicaid'' and all her medical expenses will be paid, she said. But to be eligible, she would have to quit her job. `` I want to work, I want to help and do things on my own,'' she said. The state this year will allow disabled adults like her husband to buy into the Medicaid program according to their ability to pay. And in 1992, most employers will be required to offer health insurance to employees working at least 20 hours per week.
</TEXT>
