<FIRST>r a AM-HealthCare-Glance     04-23 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Care-Glance,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Health Care Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are highlights of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' universal health care law to make affordable insurance available to all residents by 1992. About 600,000 residents, roughly one of 10 people in the state, are uninsured.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>STATE COST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ Gov <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says the four-year phase-in will cost the state $ 645.2 million, minus about $ 22.5 million in projected Medicaid cost-cutting. But some estimates have run as high as $ 1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ADMINISTRATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A Department of Medical Security will be created to: _ Manage hospitals' indigent care pools _ Develop a program of supplemental health insurance for disabled adults and _ Oversee state-brokered pooled insurance for uninsured individuals and businesses with up to six full-time employees _ Set up a sliding fee schedule based on ability to pay for participants in supplemental and individual pooled state plans
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS MANDATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ Most employers must provide health insurance to employees by Jan. 1, 1992, or pay an unemployment surcharge equal to 12 percent of the first $ 14,000 of an employee's wages, or $ 1,680 per worker To avoid surcharge, an employer must offer a health plan in which the employer's contribution is at least $ 1,680 per employee. _ Employer coverage must be offered to full-time employees working at least 30 hours per week and part-time employees working at least 20 hours per week _ Any business with less than six employees is exempt
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS INCENTIVES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ Any business not offering employee health insurance previously would be able to take an income and excise tax credit the first year equaling 20 percent of health insurance premium; 10 percent the second year
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COVERAGE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ Specific coverage requirements of employers will be decided by the new department But the plans must contain basic coverages required of all health policies under state law _ in-patient and out-patient acute hospital and physician services, diagnostic and screening tests, preventive care, prenatal and well-baby care and medically necessary emergency health services.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COLLEGES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ All colleges and universities must provide health insurance for full-time students by Sept. 1, 1989
</TEXT>
