<HEAD>Shultz Admits Clashes with Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> acknowledged Saturday he had many differences in his talks with General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, but he tried to minimize the disagreements. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, speaking with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, had made a scathing attack on the `` sermons'' he said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had delivered about Soviet behavior. The Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, in a dispatch distributed Friday after <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> ended two days of talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, quoted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as telling <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> that U.S.-Soviet relations `` are in need of a drastic restructuring.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> complained that `` everything that has been achieved in Soviet-American relations is being ascribed to the policy of strength and putting pressure on the Soviets.'' He accused <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials of constantly barraging their Soviet counterparts with `` demands, terms and grievances'' about human rights in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` We are not going to re-educate the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and do not recognize it has any right to re-educate us,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. The Soviet leader was most distressed with a speech in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, on Thursday in which <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> complained about Soviet aggression worldwide. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that until it ended, `` the world can not know true peace.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, on a sightseeing tour of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, the capital of the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, said the superpowers have had `` lots of difficulties as well as lots of accomplishments.'' `` There have been some very tough parts to every meeting on both sides,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` He has things to say. I have things to say, and there are always some informative parts and there are positive parts.'' Later, flying from <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, the capital of the Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials sought again to convince reporters that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s statement did not represent new strains with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. As if to underscore that the dialogue will continue, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, announced that <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> would meet with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> May 11-12 to continue preparations for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s summit with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> May 29-June 2. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> called the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> account and stories based on it `` overblown,'' and he defended <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s tough rhetoric. `` I think perhaps there is an overreaction to the <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> speech,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` The president has always taken the view, that I agree with, that we have to state our views realistically all the time. And we have to act in terms of the things we think need to be done.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he would keep stressing a need to improve human rights conditions in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Little progress was reported on the focus of <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, negotiating a treaty to cut in half the superpowers' arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> for sightseeing before heading Sunday for <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> to brief the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> on his <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> talks. In <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, the Ukrainian capital, he visited the site of a World War II German atrocity. `` We have to say to ourselves always, never again,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> declared in tribute to the 30,000 Jews and 70,000 other Ukrainians the German invaders herded into a ravine at <PERSON> Babi </PERSON> <PERSON> Yar </PERSON> and machine-gunned in September 1941. Stressing the heavy Jewish toll, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` This was among the first places where we saw the holocaust and the slaughter of Jews.'' His visit fell on the Jewish Sabbath. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> laid a wreath at a monument the Soviets erected in 1976 and observed a minute of silence. The American envoy also visited an unfinished <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consulate in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, the third largest city in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Construction of the mission has been halted and no date has been set for completion. American officials cite security concerns, a tighter budget and congressional opposition. But <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> favors opening the consulate for the wider knowledge it would bring of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Our plan if we move ahead is to have what we call an unclassified post,'' staffed by five or six Americans, he said. The idea is not to have any sensitive material in the consulate and thereby not make it a target for Soviet eavesdropping.
