<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 100 rescue workers combed the wreckage of a grain elevator complex today for two of three men missing after an explosion leveled the facility, while boats dragged a river alongside the granary for a third man, authorities said. Friday's explosion killed two other workers at the <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growmark </ORGANIZATION> complex, and authorities said there was only a `` very small'' chance the three missing men were alive. Three others were injured in the fiery blasts. By morning, workers using bulldozers and cranes had cleared the site of about 50 percent of the twisted metal, chunks of concrete and piles of corn and soybeans left strewn over the site by the explosion, said an official at the disaster command post who would not identify himself. Dogs were used to sniff through the grain piles but had found no sign of the missing men. Workers remained cautiously hopeful today that they might still be alive, the official said. `` It would be very small, but yes of course, there is hope,'' he said. Authorities believe the two blasts, which leveled grain silos and an office building, may have been sparked by ignited grain dust. As many as six boats dragged the <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaines </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for the body of the third missing man, who was believed to have been thrown off a barge by the force of the explosions, and four divers searched downstream Friday, authorities said. Boats continued the search today, but winds and choppy water kept divers out of the water, authorities said. A gnarled life jacket was found in the river, but there was no sign of the missing man, <LOCATION> Romeoville </LOCATION> Fire Department Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> said. The fiery blasts likened by witnesses to results of dynamite or a tornado ripped through the <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growmark </ORGANIZATION> complex along the river about 40 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> late Friday morning, officials said. Authorities identified the dead as <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Slatton </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, 20, of Anchor. Both worked at the elevator, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> part time while he studied agriculture at <ORGANIZATION> Joliet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Joliet Police Sgt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxon </PERSON> identified the missing as <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dupris </PERSON>, 23, of <PERSON> Bourbonnais </PERSON>, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Zack </PERSON>, 30, of <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION>. The explosions shattered windows in homes east of the elevator complex and sprayed grain and rubble, burying a tractor-trailer rig. `` I thought it sounded like a tornado or something,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Butterfield </PERSON>, 64, a <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION> farmer who witnessed the blast. `` I started running, but I was knocked down.'' He said he was rolling on the ground when he saw the four, 100-foot concrete silos falling. `` It was falling straight down like it had disintegrated,'' he said. `` It's gone, totaled, level complete _ just like dynamite.'' Authorities suspect grain dust may have caused the first explosion, which apparently ruptured a natural gas main about 11 a.m. and touched off a second blast moments later, said <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION> Fire Chief <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Plese </PERSON>. `` Fairly heavy levels of dust, almost like a dense fog,'' would have had to accumulate to set off such a powerful blast, said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, a safety manager with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION> Fire Batallion Chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Colbert </PERSON> said the dust can be `` highly volatile, like petroleum.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchalfen </PERSON>, a security guard at the facility, said there had been four silos at the site, and only a sheet-metal covered grain dryer remained standing. One of the silos, each of which could hold about 100,000 bushels, crushed the adjacent one-story office building. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Contos </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION>, a boat pilot working near the elevator site, said the second blast was `` just like a big ball of flame the whole length of the elevator.'' Two people were taken to <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. One of them, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rayburn </PERSON>, 40, of <PERSON> Papineau </PERSON> was in fair condition, while the second man was released, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oudt </PERSON>. A third injured worker was treated and released from <ORGANIZATION> Silver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>.
