<HEAD>Precede PHILADELPHIA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said Saturday he's not sure <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is even interested in the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket, adding that he and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> have `` one overriding goal'' _ a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> victory in November. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor continued to take shots at the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on a variety of issues, testing themes for the fall campaign now that he has moved into a commanding position in the Democratic nomination fight. Foreign policy and Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s problems at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> were his targets for Saturday. `` I'm not here to beat up on the current administration _ they have have enough problems _ and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> especially these days, if there is a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told about 300 people at the old <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> Steel headquarters in the <LOCATION> Lehigh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaigned hard across <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> in preparation for Tuesday's primary. He also made a quick trip to <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, in advance of that state's May 3 balloting. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> faced each other in a second debate in as many days in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> Saturday night. At the <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> event, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was asked about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s interest in the vice presidential nomination `` That is not what he said. I asked him if he were interested but he did n't tell me,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said of an exchange they had in the Friday night debate in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` As you could see last night, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> and I have a very good relationship. We respect each other,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` We happen to be very positive people. We both understand that there is one overriding goal in this campaign and that is to win in November.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has a big lead in the polls in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, which has a beauty contest primary and separate elections for national convention delegates. `` Every single primary is important. Please do n't pay any attention to the polls,'' he told the union members. `` We need a big turnout. Everybody has to vote. And you have to vote not only for me but for my delegates.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> began his day standing in front of the freighter Tradewind at dockside in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, talking of federal-local partnerships when music suddenly blared. `` What have we got here, a symphony behind me?'' said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, turning toward the ship. Then he noticed the Greek flag being waved from the ship's bridge `` We're going to have a brief pause while we all appreciate this,'' which he said sounded like a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> battle hymn from the Revolution fo 1821. `` This is too much.'' The Greek-American politician is a far more relaxed campaigner now that he has opened a big lead over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. He mixes pleas for a big turnout Tuesday with themes that he would use as the party's nominee in the fall `` We're going to take back the presidency for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and for the country in November. It's out there to be won. The people of this countryare ready for a change. You know and I know. We hear it every day,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told about 100 people at a <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> hall, his second stop Saturday morning. `` They want an Attorney General we can be proud of, not an <ORGANIZATION> Atorney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> we're embarrassed about.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> recalls his upset in the 1978 Democratic primary _ when he as the incumbent lost to a lesser-know conservative candidate after leading by 50 points in the polls. `` We were all looking at our statistics and we were n't remembering that it's out on the ballfield where you have to win that game,'' he said As he has in recent days since his major <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> vicory last Tuesday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> have emphasized the tone he wants to set in the campaign, a theme those who appear with him have adopted. `` He's going to take the high road all the way to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and all the way to the White House,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Borski </PERSON>, D-Pa., introducing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at the union hall In particuarly, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> rejects any suggestion of criticism of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` It's important that we run a strong and positive campaign,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are interested in what I think of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or what he thinks of me. They want to know what kind of leadership we're going to provide for this country. They want to know whether I have the strenght, the values, the experience and and the ability to lead this country'' He has also been working on how to include his cousin <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> _ who won an Oscar for best supporting actress two weeks ago _ in his stump speech. `` This has been an incredible two weeks for the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> family ... Who else but my cousin would hold up that <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> in front of a billion and half of people and say ` Okay, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> let's go.' `` That's our cry _ ` Let's go'.'' ~
