<HEAD>Reagan Warns Iran Against Continued Military, Terrorist Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf, But the, to make clear that Monday action was
taken under old policy; INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf, `We have,'
with Aspin comments; DELETES last graf to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> warned <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s leaders Saturday that continued attacks on neutral countries and refusal to negotiate an end to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war `` will be very costly to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and its people.'' The president, in his weekly radio address delivered from Camp David, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said, `` We do not seek to confront <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>.'' But, he said, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s `` leaders must understand that continued military and terrorist attacks against non-belligerents and refusal to negotiate an end to the war will be very costly to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and its people.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s tough comments came a day after administration officials let it be known that under a new policy, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will allow <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> warships to assist neutral vessels under attack in the gulf. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, while remaining officially neutral in the 7 -LCB- - year-old Iran-Iraq war, has guarded American-flagged Kuwaiti tankers from attack since last summer But the escort policy was expanded to allow <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships to aid neutral merchant ships under attack after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frigate <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> struck a mine in the gulf on April 14. Under the old rules, which permitted retaliation only for attacks on American-flagged ships, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces retaliated last Monday, sinking or crippling six Iranian vessels that challenged them after the Americans destroyed two offshore platforms. `` The actions that our forces took in the gulf were a measured response to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s resumption of mine laying and continued aggression against non-belligerents,'' the president said. `` We have completed these self-defense actions and consider this incident closed.'' In a statement on the gulf Saturday, Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must face the issue of whether an intelligence failure was involved in the Iranian mine-laying incident `` <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s minelayers have clearly found a large hole in our procedures _ a hole large enough to drive at least two minefields through,'' he said. `` We have to assume, for planning purposes, that more minefields have already been laid, and we also have to assume that more minefields will now be laid.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> had said earlier that he suspected the mines were not laid on orders from the <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> government, but by revolutionary malcontents. `` Regardless of who in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> ordered the minelaying, we are back to a state of confrontation,'' he said Saturday. The president, in his radio speech, said that he is `` extremely proud of the courage and resourcefulness of our military personnel in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Their performance under very difficult circumstances has been superb. `` We are also very pleased with the role that the European allies are playing in a cooperative effort to counter the Iranian mining threat and to help protect freedom of navigation. Such cooperative efforts, supported by our gulf <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> friends, offer the best means of deterring <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and enhancing gulf security.'' `` Working together, we can also put new life into the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to end the increasingly bloody, inhumane Iran-Iraq war and remove the root cause of tensions in the gulf,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said.
