<SECOND>AM-Crisis Center,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama May Be First State To Get `Survivable' Shelter For
Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NEWBERRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> has been chosen as the site for the nation's first survivable state emergency operating center, a disaster-proof shelter designed to allow state government to keep running even during a nuclear attack. `` Many EOC's date back to the 1950s,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McAda </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're looking for a modern approach to civil defense. If funding is approved by the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, the facility would provide safe haven for the governor and other top officials to direct evacuation procedures and other emergency operations during a nuclear attack. `` The population would be in disarray,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. `` They would be confused and afraid. ... They would have confidence in those they have placed in high public office.'' The federal agency chose <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> to receive $ 1.1 million in funding to build the center, but only if <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> provides matching funds. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said the state was chosen based on its letter of intent guaranteeing the center would provide for the number of state officials and personnel needed to coordinate disaster operations and resources. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said recently that the facility has not yet been designed, but it would have to be a subterranean, windowless facility capable of accommodating as many as 270 members of state government `` necessary to ensure a return to normalcy.'' That would include the governor, top Cabinet officials, legislative leaders and judges. Walls several feet thick would protect inhabitants from radioactivity and a ventilation system would filter the air. <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> would be dug to provide an adequate water supply for at least two weeks. `` It would not be the Grand Hotel,'' said <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, referring to an exclusive resort on Mobile Bay. `` It would provide food, clothing and shelter.'' More importantly, <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said, would be the center's state-of-the-art communications capability, including retractable antennas and equipment that would be functional even under radioactive conditions Such technology already is in place at federal facilities. `` During a nuclear exchange, the atmosphere would eliminate radio communications,'' he said. `` Our facility would be the national model of a communications system that can function regardless of the situation.'' In addition to a nuclear attack, the center could be used during hurricanes, tornadoes or any other natural or technological disaster, such as a crisis at the state's two nuclear power plants. <PERSON> McAda </PERSON> said most states have some kind of emergency operations center, but <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> determined in a recent study that their capabilities were `` low and declining.'' `` The continuity of government concept is one that <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> will be pursuing very vigorously in the future,'' said <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>.
