<HEAD>President Crippled By Submission To US, Politicians and Diplomats
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Politicians and diplomats say President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON>'s already weak government has been crippled because of its apparent inability to stand up to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Interviews with prominent Hondurans, as well as talks with foreign envoys and people in the street, indicated that citizens of this old friend of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are peeved with what they see as Yankee high-handedness. Local politicians said a series of events have prompted a fundamental review of U.S.-Honduran relations, which they said probably will change definitively, if not drastically. In recent days, Hondurans have bristled at the transportation of a Honduran national to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on cocaine charges, done even though the Honduran Constitution prohibts extradition of Honduran citizens. Many are angry about the use of Honduran territory by the U.S.-backed Contra rebels in their fight against the Nicarguan government. And the maneuvers of 3,200 American troops in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> last month were also seen by many as another example of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dominance. Even a presidential decision Monday to award a multimillion-dollar compensation to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen whose farm was expropriated in 1982 has incurred the people's wrath. `` Yankee garbage out of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>,'' and `` If the <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> do n't get out, in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> they will die,'' about 2,000 people chanted as they marched in the capital Thursday The chants, which rhyme in Spanish, would have sounded foreign on so many voices just a few months ago. The march came two weeks after a mob sacked and burned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate. The demonstrators, like others, say <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON>'s submission to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wishes in recent months has reached the point where Honduran insitutions, including the Constitution, are blatantly ignored. Despite the ire of the students who made up the core of the marchers, most Hondurans are far from anti-American. Those consulted last week seemed especially hurt because the perceived slights are coming from a friend. `` <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> as an individual has no importance. He was just a detonator,'' said <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Acosta </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>, a lawyer and member of the directorate of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He was referring to <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Matta </PERSON>, who was arrested April 5 and hustled out of the country and into the federal penetentiary in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, by Honduran authorities working closely with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. <PERSON> Matta </PERSON>, considered an international cocaine kingpin, was one of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Druge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s most wanted men. `` If they can kidnap <PERSON> Matta </PERSON>, they can kidnap anybody's brother,'' said truck driver <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lezama </PERSON>. `` The servileness of this president has no name.'' `` There is complete indignation because of poor management of this -LRB- <PERSON> Matta </PERSON> -RRB- situation,'' said <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and a presidential hopeful for <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in fall 1989 elections. `` The image of <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> has been eroded,'' he said. But <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON> said he does n't think a military coup is possible. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would cut off aid, and the economic situation here would go from bad to worse,'' he said. The armed forces governed <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> for nearly 20 years before a return to civilian rule in 1982. The military still continues to exercise much political power. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> is one of the poorest countries in the hemisphere, with 50 percent unemployment or underemployment, 60 percent illiteracy and a per capita annual gross national product of just over $ 750. <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislator, agreed that a coup was almost out of the question `` because everyone involved would lose.'' He said these are trying times for what had until a few months ago been an island of relative tranquility amid <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s turmoil `` But some good comes out of this,'' he said. `` It will make the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> realize its relations with <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> must be profoundly reanalyzed.'' According to <PERSON> Acosta </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>, `` It does n't matter that the small left takes up this banner of resentment. But it -LRB- the resentment -RRB- will consolidate the broader center-left for a revision of the status quo.'' <PERSON> Meza </PERSON> said the presidential candidate who taps into this resentment will have an advantage. `` Our presidential campaign is virtually underway,'' he said, `` and no one who hopes to win can fail to take this resentment into account.''
