light came after a 36-member team of <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> experts waited for three weeks on the wind-swept island of <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> for a suitable day to attempt the flight. Essential requirements were a calm sea, southerly winds of less than 3 knots, temperatures under 70 degress Fahrenheit and visibility to the horizon, according to <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bussolari </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> aeronautics professor in charge of flight operations. `` Conditions for the flight were ideal. We even had a southerly tailwind,'' <PERSON> Bussolari </PERSON> said. The southerly tailwind pushed the <ORGANIZATION> Daedalus </ORGANIZATION> 88 over the Agean waters at a rate faster than expected by the <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> team, with the plane averaging 18.5 miles per hour, team officials said. They had not expected the ungainly flying machine to go over 14 miles per hour. `` We were predicting the low speeds because we had been estimating headwinds, which are prevalent. We have no idea where the tailwinds came from,'' said project news director <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>. In addition to <PERSON> Kanellopoulos </PERSON>, three other athlete-pilots had been standing by for 48 hours each in readiness for a possible record flight. They were <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Scioscia </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Zack </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and 27-year-old Tremml, the former world-record holder and a medical student from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>.
