<HEAD>With ^BC-France-Election, ran in advance as b0511</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 French voters enjoyed a lull Saturday on the eve of elections expected to determine who eventually faces off with President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, a Socialist acting like a social institution these days. Since the hectic two-week official campaign ended Friday, the silence has been resounding. No media appearances or campaigning were allowed on Saturday. Even the political grease of voter surveys had run dry. French law prohibits polls in the week before the elections. Even so, voters had plenty to spin their wheels over. The confrontation marks the first time in the 30 years of the Fifth Republic that a president and his own premier have faced one another in a presidential election. All polls predict that <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, the 71-year-old president seeking a second seven-year term, will square off in the May 8 runoff with <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s 55-year-old conservative premier. They have `` cohabitated,'' as the French put it, since the right's victory in parliamentary elections in 1986. The main interest in Sunday's voting, then, was reduced to numbers: _ What percentage will <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> win? Will he be able to pick up enough Communist and centrist votes to expand the 35-37 percent the polls give him? _ What will be the combined totals of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, predicted to gain 22-24 percent, and former center-right premier <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, 16-17 percent? That number could give a good idea whether anyone can beat <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the final round of voting. Besides <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, 68-year-old <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> is the only other candidate with a whisper of a chance to make it to the runoff. He was long the top rightist candidate before nose-diving in the polls in the past two months. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> has said he ca n't be counted out now. But he pledges to support <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> if the premier comes out ahead in first-round voting. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> has vowed to do the same. Much also depends on backers of extreme right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s strident anti-immigration and `` French first'' appeal has won over an estimated 10-12 percent of the electorate in an otherwise lackluster campaign. Actually, voters will choose from nine candidates Sunday. Theoretically, it is possible to elect a president in the first round, but the large number of candidates means that no one can expect to win the required absolute majority of votes. Other candidates in the race are <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoinie </PERSON>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate; <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Juquin </PERSON>, leader of a splinter <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> reformist movement; ecologist <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Waechter </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> Trotskyist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arlette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laguiller </ORGANIZATION>; and another Trotskyist, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Boussel </PERSON>. The polls predict <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> will win the runoff no matter who he faces. He has reshaped his image toward the center in recent months and has even been dubbed by the French with the avuncular nickname of `` Tonton.'' But <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> was closing the gap when the final surveys were published a week ago. Moreoever, the undecided vote was high, as much as 20 percent. Many political analysts say <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> must get 35 percent in the first round in order to win May 8. On the right, it was generally thought that the combined Chirac-Barre vote must total at least 43 percent to give conservatives a chance in the runoff. However, many of <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>'s more centrist supporters may abandon <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> in the second round. The polls open 8 a.m. Sunday and close in most areas at 6 p.m. In major urban areas, however, they remain open until 8 p.m. None of the candidates has come out with a detailed program, focusing instead on generalities. In his last television speech, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> stressed the need for `` solidarity, equality of opportunity'' and the `` refusal of privileges'' for some people. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> has responded by accusing <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> of `` proposing nothing precise for our country.'' He stands on his two-year record as head of the government, which he says started the country on the road back to prosperity.
