<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friends, admirers and political allies of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, assassinated as he sought the presidency 20 years ago, were reunited Saturday at a conference to remember the senator and seek lessons from his life. `` R.F.K. Remembered'' is `` partially a reunion but also, and more significantly, a reaffirmation and rededication ... to the purposes for which <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> lived and died,'' historian <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marymount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> audience, setting the theme for the conference. <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, who served as an adviser to <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s slain brother, President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, received a standing ovation from a packed auditorium of onetime <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> supporters, friends and classes of youngsters who came to learn about the candidate they never knew. One of <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s 11 children, lawyer <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>, also was to speak. Other participants included <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s former press secretary, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mankiewicz </PERSON>, former <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Guthman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, former <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration aide <PERSON> Midge </PERSON> <PERSON> Costanza </PERSON> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Assemblyman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>. `` Twenty years ago this month many of us were working our heads and hearts