e second gun being fired at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>. Last week's release of police files in the nearly 20-year-old case has focused attention on conspiracy theories and the circumstances surrounding <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s death <PERSON> Schrade </PERSON>, who organized the conference, was chagrined at the timing of the release of files he had sought for years. `` I thought it was monstrous bad timing by -LRB- Secretary of State -RRB- March <PERSON> Fong </PERSON> <PERSON> Eu </PERSON>,'' he said, noting he had asked her to postpone the release until the conference was over. <PERSON> Schrade </PERSON> said the release focused attention again on <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s death while the conference was meant to shift that focus to his life `` All of the pain and grief had buried a lot of the legacy,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> was the best political candidate I've known in 40 years in politics,'' said <PERSON> Schrade </PERSON>. `` He was committed to real social change, to ending the war in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. He was committed to working for the underclass in this country.'' During a panel discussion, <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, a leader of the 1968 riots at the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Democratic Convention, said he believed that the violence at the convention would not have occurred had <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> been the candidate. `` That would have been a convention without chaos,'' <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> said, `` because <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> could work with -LRB- Mayor -RRB- <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. Anyone who could work with <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was quite a fellow.'' Among spectators at the conference was former <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who said he came because <PERSON> Schrade </PERSON> was his next-door neighb