<HEAD>Protest in Second Day at Liberal Arts School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters joined in singing `` We Shall Overcome'' and offered advice Saturday to minority students who occupied a building at <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> for a second day to protest racial policies at the school. Parents' Weekend is under way at the 2,000-student liberal-arts college. An afternoon rally outside <ORGANIZATION> Jenness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, where the occupation was taking place, drew about 80 people including parents and faculty. The crowd, predominately white, sang the civil rights movement anthem and listened to about 40 minutes of speeches by the protesters, said college news director <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Berek </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON>, 21, a junior from <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, was among the protesters who came out of the building to address the crowd. `` Our efforts are part of efforts initiated four years ago to raise concerns about the presence of minority faculty here, minority concerns in the curriculum and minority students at the school,'' <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON>, who is black, said in an interview. `` There's a very strong sense of frustration, a sense of inertia. There's certainly sympathy, but over the years the school has failed to take forceful steps,'' he said. Minorities make up a record 28 percent of the 1,207 students just accepted for the fall incoming freshman class, Ms. <PERSON> Berek </PERSON> said. At present, members of minorities make up 13 percent of the student body and 10 percent of the 278-teacher faculty. About 30 students stayed in the building overnight; an additional 30 or 40 came in and out during the day, <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON> said. Parents visiting the occupied building included veterans of the civil rights movement who shared advice on how students should conduct themselves. White students were not allowed among