<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first World Cup Chess Tournament closed Saturday and experts said the victorious <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> remains a force in the game and a threat to champion <PERSON> Garri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>. The tournament was the first of six competitons that form the World Cup championship. Soviet grandmaster <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> won the the $ 20,000 top prize Friday by scoring 11 points out of a possible 16, a point ahead of fellow Soviet <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Salov </PERSON>. The World Cup series was organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Grandmasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a body set up in 1986 at the urging of champion <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, also of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, to increase the influence of the game's leading grandmasters. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> and other grandmasters have feuded often with the the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, the game's governing body. Experts said during closing ceremonies Saturday that <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> remains a major threat to <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>'s supremacy. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>, who did not compete in this tournament, beat <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> in 1985 to become the world champion. `` This was a normal result for <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>. He's the second-best player in the world and there is clearly a big gap between second and third in the world at the moment,'' said <PERSON> Leontxo </PERSON> <PERSON> Garica </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> chess commentator. In the World Cup series, each of the world's 25 leading grandmasters will compete in four of the six events. The winner of the cup will be the player with the best three results. Third place on Friday was shared by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, Yugoslav Gran