<HEAD>Sister Supports Use of Brother's Heart Before He Was Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The use of a brain-dead man's heart for a transplant before he was identified was justified because it helped save another life, the man's sister said. The transplant was criticized Friday by medical ethicists. `` I'm happy that at least, even if his body is dead, his heart is beating in another person,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Celsa </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, 20, sister of <PERSON> Eleno </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulloa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, 19. `` I'm also very satisfied with the explanation that they gave me, the authorities.'' <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> was found unconscious with no identification on a <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> street early Tuesday and declared brain dead the next day after surgery to remove a clot in the brain. Police believe he was the victim of a blow to the head. Before he was identified, doctors at Hoag Memorial Hospital Presbyterian transplanted his heart into Dr. <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphreys </PERSON>, 58, a retired <LOCATION> Fountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> physician suffering from a degenerative heart disease. A nursing supervisor who declined to give her name said Saturday that <PERSON> Humphreys </PERSON>' condition was listed as critical but stable. <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>'s heart was transplanted under a state law that allows removal of an organ without the permission of the donor or his family if police are unable to identify someone after making a diligent effort for 24 hours. His relatives did n't find out his heart was transplanted until Friday. `` I think it was good what they did, taking my brother's heart,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> said Friday `` They saved another life. Yes, it is painful for us, but we have to accept the reality of it.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> said she last saw her brother on Monday, and that on Tuesday, her father, contacted her and said he had been unable to reach his son. A friend who wo