<HEAD>Bitter Aftertaste Lingers A Year After Services Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year after Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> signed one of the more controversial levies in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> history, lawmakers are avoiding tax talk because of battles that left many licking political wounds in an election year. One year ago Saturday, <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> signed a bill initiating a 5 percent tax on service industries ranging from lawn care to law and from accounting to advertising. The tax sparked an outcry from many service groups, and companies such as <ORGANIZATION> Lever </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON> withdrew local advertising of national brands. The protests prompted <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> to reverse himself and lead a successful drive to repeal the tax and replace it with a sales tax increase. But the wear and tear of the tax battle is still evident, and some say the state merely put off a long-term revenue problem. The Legislature, which is three weeks into this year's two-month regular session, shows signs of burnout after five special sessions in the last 15 months. `` I think the session in terms of actually starting has almost been delayed by the backup of special sessions and the result of everything that has happened in the last year,'' said House Speaker <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>. Three of the five sessions concerned the services tax, which had been heralded as fair because it tapped the state's fastest growing economic sector and because higher-income people purchase more services than those with lower incomes. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, a self-proclaimed fiscal conservative who does not face re-election until 1990, still is working to rebuild his tarnished standing with voters. Proponents of the services tax said it would ensure adequate revenue to provide services to the state's burgeoning population, and they were outraged when <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> flip-flopped on the measure last August. The governor also angered Republicans because he pushed for a 1 percentage point increase in sales tax as a replacement instead of meeting a 1986 campaign pledge to cut $ 800 million from state spending. In his State of the State address earlier this month, <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> promised to veto any tax bill sent to his desk this year. `` The governor has not intentions of supporting the services tax again,'' press secretary <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> said. But some legislators, including <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, predict that the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> is likely to consider another services tax eventually. The boost in the sales tax to 6 percent, which took effect Feb. 1, is projected to raise $ 1 billion this year, just as the services tax was expected to do. But economists say the services tax would produce more revenue over time as the state's services sector grows, revenue that some lawmakers believe is badly needed. The governor has proposed a $ 20.3 billion budget for the fiscal year beginning July 1, up from $ 18.5 billion this year. Many Democratics say even that increase would not satisfy the needs of a growing population _ the state had just over 12 million residents in 1987 and officials say it is growing by up to 1,000 people a day _ and correct for previous inadequacies in some programs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> must reach a budget compromise by July 1. The governor has proposed increasing fees for such things as state university tuition, fishing licenses, and environmental permits. Lawmakers have quietly discussed increasing gasoline taxes to help pay for transportation needs, but no formal proposal has been launched and <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> has refused to consider such a plan.
