that empire,'' said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> also scoffed at reports that some opposition figures and the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> have been secretly trying to negotiate his resignation with his supporters, including leaders of the major pro-government political party. `` It's too bad they're not talking with Gen. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>,'' the general said, adding that many opposition leaders `` are trying to ride the wave and gain prestige.'' `` They all want to be like <PERSON> Monsignor </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, they want to be like <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> or the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo is the Catholic archbishop of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> who has mediated talks between that government and rebels <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Cerezo </ORGANIZATION> are the presidents of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> who pushed for those negotiations. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> hierachy called on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration Friday to end its sanctions against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and said the country has suffered enough. `` We can not continue like this,'' the church said in an eight-page pastoral letter signed by Archbishop <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> and the nation's 10 bishops. Describing the sanctions as the cause of `` misery and desperation'' for thousands of Panamanians, the letter said they go beyond `` any strategy of political pressure and constitute by 