<HEAD>300 Mark 300th Anniversary of Quaker Slavery Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The memory of an anti-slavery protest by Quakers 300 years ago should stir consciences against modern-day injustices, a group that marked the event was told Saturday. `` I think the real question that we should be asking ourselves today, especially those of us who are white, is how in the name of God could it be that it has taken us 300 years to get rid of racism and we still have n't done it,'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cary </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said. `` The only thing that I can think of that's encouraging is that for the past 35 years, we've been gaining on it.'' <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> spoke to about 300 people at a vacant lot in the city's <LOCATION> Germantown </LOCATION> section, which was the site of a house where where <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastorius </PERSON> and three other <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quakers </ORGANIZATION> in 1688 drafted one of the earliest recorded protests against slavery, according to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germantown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protest </ORGANIZATION>, the organization that sponsored the gathering The statement was forwarded to larger Quaker assemblies, which tabled it. It was not until 1776 that <PERSON> Quakers </PERSON>, who became leaders of the abolition movement, forbade slaveholding by their members. In 1780, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> became the first state to pass a law phasing out slavery. One speaker told the audience that the German and Dutch Quakers who authored the statement saw only the beginnings of a rigid form of slavery. `` We think of their protest as a protest against something that was in place. It was not,,'' said <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Germantown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and a history professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> `` It was a brave and courageous thing in a new land with a new language for them to do.'' The organizers of the commemoration drew up a petition called `` 1988 <LOCATION> Germantown </LOCATION> Protest,'' which said, `` Our <LOCATION> Germantown </LOCATION> forbears would have us stand today with the homeless, the hungry, the unemployed and the neglected.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpkins </PERSON>, a retired tax assessor, said the need for protests still existed. `` Today, the idea of slavery of men does n't exist, but the shortcomings of life such as a lack of decent housing, waste of youth and other areas where the quality of life is wanting,'' <PERSON> Simpkins </PERSON> said.
