Pittsburgh </LOCATION> area. In <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, who put his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination on hold Thursday, scored big gains as the state's Democrats elected national delegates at congressional district conventions Saturday. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, however, claimed most of the delegates elected, winning 12, while <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> got seven and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> five, with two others elected as uncommitted. That breakdown will dictate how 13 more <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> delegates are elected at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> on May 14, when <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will claim seven more and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> will split the other six at-large delegates. The latest <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> delegate count gave <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 1,075.15 and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the only other active candidate, 836.1. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has 427.55 and uncommitted number 599.75. A total of 2,081 was needed for the nomination. In a reminder that there still was a race for the Republican nomination, however lopsided, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> captured the lion's share of 20 delegates chosen Saturday at the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Republican Convention The former television evangelist picked up 14 delegates, his biggest one-day showing so far and his first delegate gain since Super Tuesday, while Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won four delegates and another two were elected as uncommitted. But the victory still left <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> more than 1,000 delegates behind <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the all but certain <OR