<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A London-bound <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet with more than 200 people aboard returned to the <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, airport after a cockpit indicator light showed a problem with a hydraulic line, a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The light came on shortly after takeoff Thursday night from <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, and the pilot requested permission to return to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> as a precaution to have fixed the line, which serves an engine, spokesman <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said at company headquarters in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. The line was replaced, and the 747 jet went on to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, has been the subject of government safety inspections. Eastern was fined $ 823,000 two weeks ago for safety violations.
