<HEAD>Christian Science Monitor Launches New Monthly Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just a week after announcing plans for a half-hour nightly news program, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION> says it will publish a new monthly magazine, `` World Monitor.'' The first issue of the glossy, four-color monthly will appear in September, at the same time the TV show begins. The magazine will include articles on world news, politics, the arts, economics, culture and personalities with what is described as a `` global focus.'' `` We're hoping to throw a life preserver to people who are drowning in a tidal wave of facts, info, dis-info and mis-info,'' said `` World Monitor'' Editor in Chief <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Foell </PERSON>, who is also editor of the Christian Science Monitor, flagship of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, associate publisher of `` World Monitor,'' said marketing studies found there was a demand for the `` big-picture'' journalism that both the television show and magazine will offer. `` We saw that the newsweekly concept was being covered well but that many people wanted more than headline type news,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. In addition to the newspaper, magazine and TV show, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION> also offers radio news programming and a worldwide radio shortwave radio system. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said Monitor executives hope to make a profit with the magazine, which will have a newsstand price of $ 2.50. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monitor </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, with a circulation of about 200,000, has lost money for years.
