<HEAD>With AM-L'Ambiance Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the men who crawled beneath crushed cement to search for survivors in the collapse of the <LOCATION> L'Ambiance </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> building now is looking for a job on a rescue team. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Tufaro </PERSON>, nicknamed `` the Mole'' during the nine-day rescue attempt that began April 23, 1987, was one of the short, wiry men who tied ropes around themselves, crawled under the ruins and searched in vain for survivors. Twenty-eight men were killed in the collapse; 14 were injured. <PERSON> Tufaro </PERSON> has a scrapbook full of newspaper clippings about his rescue efforts, but he does n't have what he wants most _ a job with a rescue team. <PERSON> Tufaro </PERSON>, 25, completed a course in firefighter training in November at the <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, paid for by a $ 1,200 donation from a <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> bank. He works as a carpenter, the kind of job he held before the collapse. He has contacted an aide to Gov. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> to ask when the state will set up a disaster response team. He said he was told that thg team will be set up when funds are available. <PERSON> Tufaro </PERSON> said the L'Ambiance tragedy enabled him to discover what he wants to do with his life, but he said he is frustrated because he ca n't find a job.
