<HEAD>U.S. Navy Detonates Three Mines In Central Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iraq-Faw, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout report with of 5 mines detonated,
Washington report of new orders for Navy in gulf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> mine sweepers detonated mines Friday that were found earlier in the week near an offshore Iranian oil platform in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and shipping executives reported. In another development, officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has decided to permit <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships in the gulf to intervene with force to help neutral merchant vessels that are attacked. Their orders have been to offer only humanitarian assistance. Shipping executives said three mines were detonated Friday but <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, speaking privately, said mine sweepers examined and destroyed five mines. They said the explosives carried serial numbers indicating <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> manufactured them. The mines were spotted by a French warship Tuesday near the <LOCATION> Sassan </LOCATION> oil platform about 80 miles from the <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> peninsula. The area was declared a navigational hazard and commercial vessels were warned to stay away. <ORGANIZATION> Sassan </ORGANIZATION> is one of two Iranian platforms the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> destroyed Monday in retaliation for a mine explosion that damaged the frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> last week and wounded 10 sailors. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and other nations' mine sweepers have worked all week to clear a mine field about 70 miles northeast of where the mines were detonated Friday. That field is in a main shipping channel for reflagged Kuwaiti tankers escorted by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships. Escort operations, which began last July, have been suspended until the mines are cleared. At least three of the 11 Kuwaiti tankers given <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags and registration were anchored outside the gulf Friday. Under the new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships no longer would be instructed to stay away when <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> attacks merchant ships sailing under other flags. If a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warship observed an Iranian raid and was close enough to intervene it would have the authority to do so, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` It's a random, target-of-opportunity approach designed to throw the Iranians off guard,'' one said. A Capitol Hill official briefed on the matter Friday said: `` This will give a lot of authority to local commanders and a lot of leeway to do as they see fit.'' Another official said: `` Our purpose is not to get into a war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Our purpose is to secure safe passage for neutral shipping moving back and forth between neutral ports.'' They said the policy change does not extend <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military protection to convoys of foreign-flag ships. Only ships flying the American flag will be entitled to `` door-to-door protection'' in convoys, one official said.
