<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Friday accused <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> of state terrorism in the assassination of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s military commander. `` It is but another example of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s cynical contempt for world public opinion,'' Soviet Ambassador <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Belonogov </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Belonogov </PERSON> also called the slaying `` another act of the policy of state terrorism which has long been practiced by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, which requested the council meeting, wants <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> condemned for the assassination of <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON> at his home in suburban <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> last Saturday. Tunisian officials and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> sources say <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> commandos gunned down <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON>, also known as <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jihad </PERSON>. Officially, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has neither confirmed nor denied the allegations. In a carefully worded statement issued Thursday by the Israeli mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, the Jewish state denied it `` admitted'' the attack, as <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> claimed. The Soviets joined a growing list of nations condemning <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for the assassination. Most have singled it out by name. A few, such as <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, have not. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s ambassador, <PERSON> Hideo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kagami </PERSON>, noted the absence of firm proof against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kagami </PERSON> said any condemnation `` must be based on solid and irrefutable evidence.'' Many diplomats said they expected <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to veto <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>'s resolution, as it has several resolutions on the unrest considered by the council recently. They said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vote hinged on the wording of the resolution. A direct condemnation of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was sure to be vetoed, but a general condemnation of political assassination might survive, said the diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity. A vote was expected Monday. Dozens of nations have joined the debate, including many accused of sponsoring terrorism, such as <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Many speakers told the council the slaying further hampers the prospects of a settlement between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> neighbors. `` The shots in <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> are shots against peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>,'' said Yugoslav Ambassador <PERSON> Dragoslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Pejic </PERSON>. A number of speakers told <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON>'s death will not end the Palestinian unrest since Dec. 8 in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> that has left 171 Palestinians and two Israelis dead. <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON>, who grew up in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, was the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> coordinator for the uprising. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> has issued orders for a `` Day of Rage'' in the Israeli-occupied terrorities Saturday to avenge <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON>, according to a leaflet circulating in the area.
