<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The concrete and steel rubble from <LOCATION> L'Ambiance </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> has long been cleared away, but the impact of the decade's most devastating construction accident still is being felt in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Lawmakers have been pushing for changes in construction-safety laws since the partially built <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, apartment complex collapsed one year ago today, leaving 28 workers dead. Proposals have ranged from tinkering with the accident reporting requirements and stiffening criminal penalties in fatal construction accidents to creating a separate construction agency outside the often-criticized <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>.
