<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When an assassination team gunned down the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s No. 2 man at his villa in <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, it was widely accepted as another daring action by the long arm of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s fabled security and intelligence services. The slaying of <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON> 1,500 miles from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> on April 16 bore the fingerprints of the Mossad, the agency responsible for activities outside <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s borders. By all accounts it was quick, decisive, carried out with split-second timing and backed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s air and naval forces. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s intelligence has been able to gather precise information on locations of homes or installations and the movements of bodyguards. Teams have been able to make pinpoint attacks and often escape without detection.
