<NOTE>For Release Monday April 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Money Manager Sees More Trouble Ahead for Stocks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market's attempt to rally since the crash last fall has failed to impress decision-makers at one of the nation's largest money-management firms. `` It is a rally in a bear market, and we are toward the end of it,'' contends <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON>, senior vice president and economist at the Pittsburgh-based <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` Whatever you regard as your ` defensive' position in regard to the stock market, we believe you should now be in it,'' <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> added in an interview. That puts him at odds with analysts at some of Wall Street's most prominent brokerage firms, who argue that the current mood of fear and pessimism is setting the stage for higher stock prices <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> agrees rallies usually exhaust themselves only when they have attracted a large following of true believers. `` I'd like to see more enthusiasm at the top,'' he acknowledges. Nevertheless, he says, spotting the precise moment when such an event occurs is a very difficult and chancy assignment. And, he adds, `` the easy money in the rally has already been made.'' Gailliot bases his reasoning on an appraisal of the `` character'' of the market's rise from its lows late last year. In the aftermath of the October crash, <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> asserted that stock prices were almost certain to rebound. However, he added at the time, the upswing itself would have to be watched for a while to see whether it looked like only a passing phenomenon or something more durable. By April 13, he concluded the rally had flunked that test. In its early stages, the market's rise produced a strong plurality of individual stocks rising in price vs. those that declined. But these `` very positive breadth characteristics'' have `` deteriorated significantly in the last month,'' he said. Meanwhile, volume of stock trading has contracted as prices have risen, he observed. `` That is a classic bear-market characteristic,'' he said. In spite of all the recent signs of strength in the economy, <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> believes a recession is lurking in the not-too-distant future. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> is being forced back into its old position of fighting inflation and defending the dollar,'' he says. `` One must remember that about one-third of all recessions are not predictable. We only know after the fact.'' But while he believes the portents are bad for stocks, <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> takes a far more upbeat view of the outlook for bonds: `` A bull market in bonds began on Black Monday,'' when 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds were yielding about 10.4 percent. From that point, prices rose and yields fell to about 8.3 percent several weeks ago. Since then, they have climbed back up to 9 percent, creating what <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> views as `` another opportunity to buy.'' Once the recession he expects manifests itself and becomes widely recognized, he maintains, the yield on long-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds could get as low as 6 percent. The recession will eventually set the stage for a new bull market that could cap off the 1980s as a true `` decade for financial assets,'' <PERSON> Gailliot </PERSON> says, but he views the investment outlook for the 1990s as less certain. By then, he says, the nation will have stretched its habit of deficit spending, of consuming more than it produces, to an important limit. At that point, he says, the world's financial markets will provide the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with only enough money to carry its existing debts, rather than to expand them. When that happens, he says, the nation will be forced into making tough choices about how to deal with its domestic and international deficits, and the choices it makes will go a long way toward determining the financial shape of the 1990s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, April 25</NOTE>
