 How many Americans are working in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and how many of those speak fluent Japanese? asks <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McIsaac </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION>. At the other end of the spectrum, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Culbertson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should wipe out its trade deficit with a single stroke by negotiating levels of imports and exports with other countries on a government level. Freely importing cheap goods from low-wage nations `` is just killing your future in the most outrageous way,'' <PERSON> Culbertson </PERSON> said Friday. In other business and economic news this past week: _ The inflation rate took its biggest jump in 14 months in March, with clothing, food and gasoline prices leading a 0.5 rise percent in consumer prices _ The federal budget deficit rose to $ 29.1 billion in March, but the deficit for the first six months of the fiscal year was 3.5 percent less than in the first half of 1987 _ Housing starts declined slightly in March because gains in construction of single-family homes failed to offset a sharp drop in apartment building _ Orders to the nation's factories for `` big ticket'' items remained strong in March The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said orders for durable goods rose less than 0.1 percent. _ <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the first of the big three automakers to report first-quarter results, said it earned $ 1.09 billion, up about 18 percent from $ 922.5 million the previous year _ Airlines offered candy as a reward and the federal government threatened $ 1,