<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 23-24,0800</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 23-24</NOTE>
<HEAD>High Court Ruling Seen as Ratifying Authority Congress Felt It Had</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling this past week that the federal government may tax interest paid on state and local government bonds was widely seen as ratifying authority <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> already felt it had. But the decision enraged one group of bond issuers who called it a `` butchery of the constitution'' and threatened `` drastic remedies if necessary'' to protect tax exemption from further erosion. Others worried the ruling may encourage a revenue-hungry <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to find ways to tax interest on such bonds to fill the gaping budget deficit. The ruling had no effect on the tax-exempt status of the estimated $ 730 billion in municipal bonds already outstanding nor on future issues, which are expected to amount to another $ 100 billion this year alone. Bond fund managers reported no significant selling in tax-exempt funds occurred after the ruling, and expressed confidence that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would never remove tax exemption retroactively anyway. But the ruling could have long-range implications for issuers who have been selling tax-exempt bonds at relatively low rates of interest for projects such as schools and roads as well as for investors who accept lower interest for their money because the payments have not been taxed by the federal government. `` We do n't take this as an inconsequential ruling,'' said <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arndt </PERSON>, a spokesman for the National League of Cities. `` It is a very big threat to the capacity of state and local revenue systems.'' The case was brought by the state of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, challenging a law requiring that state and municipal bonds be registered in the name of the owner if the interest paid is to be exempt from federal taxation. It cited the 1895 case <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> vs. Farmers' <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in which the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> held that interest earned on a state bond was exempt from federal taxation. This past Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected the challenge. In writing the majority opinion, Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said that owners of state bonds have no constitutional entitlement against having to pay federal taxes on the interest earned on the bonds. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, dissenting from the 7-1 decision, said the court overruled `` a precedent it has honored for nearly a hundred years'' and makes state and local government financing activities partly dependent on `` whether <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voluntarily abstains from tapping this permissible source of income tax revenue.'' Word of the decision initially sent tax-exempt bond prices lower, but the market quickly bounced back as traders appeared to conclude that it made no fundamental changes in how <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> viewed the issue anyway. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been legislating for some time under the presumption that the <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> decision of 1895 was obsolete,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedlander </PERSON>, managing director for municipal bond research at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The chairman of the tax-writing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has presumed for 20 years that it could enact laws involving the federal tax treatment of state and local government bonds He said there was no reason to believe that the court's latest decision `` will either prompt or deter future congressional action.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group for bond dealers, said it was `` surprised and disappointed that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> went out of its way'' to state its views on tax exemption. The group's president, <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>, said laws enacted in the past few years have chipped away at the tax-exempt status of some municipal bonds. Fears that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would enact restrictions as part of the 1986 tax law prompted issuers to sell a record $ 220 billion in new long-term municipal bonds in 1985. New-issue volume has since fallen to $ 151 billion in 1986 and $ 105 billion in 1987 and is expected to fall to $ 100 billion this year, she said. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Beals </PERSON>, the executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, said local government officials have been `` angered and disgusted by the unrelenting assault'' by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the executive branch on local revenue systems and was `` even more outraged at the willingness of the judicial branch to condone and even encourage such activities.'' `` We do not accept this butchery of the constitution and we are prepared to respond with drastic remedies if necessary,'' he said. <PERSON> Arndt </PERSON> said that among the remedies are the possibility of amending the constitution, enacting legislation to spell out the exemption or making the issue fundamental to support or opposition for political candidates.
</TEXT>
