<HEAD>Durable Goods Orders Remain Strong</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite lower-than-expected orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories in March, analysts say the economy remains strong. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that orders for durable goods, items expected to last at least three years, were virtually unchanged last month, reflecting a drop in military hardware that offset gains in other areas. That was far less than the 1.3 percent advance most economists were expecting. However, the government raised its estimate of new orders in February. The revised report shows a 0.1 percent gain for the month, rather than the previously reported 1.1 percent drop. The net result was a relatively strong level of orders through the first quarter of this year, 7.9 percent above a year ago when compared March to March. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>, said the report indicated `` modest growth in the economy, not a boom but no signs of a big dip.'' <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinner </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm, said it was premature to worry about sluggish growth in new orders because shipments remain strong and the backlog in unfilled orders remains high. But the lower-than-expected results for March, along with a stronger dollar overseas, helped both the bond and stock markets, which have been depressed over fears of inflation and higher interest rates. The key 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond's price rose about $ 5 per $ 1,000 in face amount Friday and its yield fell back under 9 percent. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 27.69 points to 2,015.09.
</TEXT>
