<SECOND>PM-Smoking Ban,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Smoking Ban Takes Effect</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new federal ban on smoking on domestic airline flights lasting under two hours went into effect at 12:01 a.m. EDT today. The new regulations, which outlaw smoking on flights of less than two hours, carry stiff fines for violations: up to $ 1,000 for smoking and $ 2,000 for tinkering with lavatory smoke alarms. They apply to around 80 percent of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flights, or an estimated 13,600 a day. Under the new rules, airlines are required to announce to passengers onboard before takeoff that smoking is prohibited on the flight, and to keep the `` No Smoking'' indicator lights illuminated for the duration of affected flights. Even if a flight is delayed in the air or on the ground and goes beyond two hours, smoking will be prohibited if the schedule has it as lasting two hours or less, according to officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to the onboard warning, many airlines are making announcements in the gate area before passengers board the plane. Travelers flying <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest carrier, are being advised individually of the new regulations when they check in. Second-ranked <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION>'s flight attendants and ticket agents have been given special instructions to inform passengers about which flights will be non-smoking, and boarding passes have been changed. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, whose tough policy goes beyond the federal requirements by banning smoking on nearly all its domestic flights, is handing out candies and mints as well as brochures to passengers. American is providing cinnamon hard candies suggested by the American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> as a substitute for cigarettes. And <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is distributing more than 430,000 pieces of a gum called `` Ban Smoke,'' designed to temporarily control the urge. Airlines say they have briefed their cabin crews on the new regulations and how to handle potentially defiant smokers. Flight attendants will tell the rebels that they are in violation of federal law and advise them of the consequences. If a passenger persists in smoking, airlines say they may notify authorities at the plane's next destination, arrange for the plane to be met by the police or even divert the aircraft in some cases involving unruly smokers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>